#. Tag: para
#: storage_raid10.xml:95
#, no-c-format
msgid "10 (1+0)"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_raid10.xml:100
#, no-c-format
msgid "RAID 0 (stripe) built with RAID 1 (mirror) arrays"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_raid10.xml:105
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"RAID 1+0 provides high levels of I/O performance, data redundancy, and disk "
"fault tolerance. Because each member device in the RAID 0 is mirrored "
"individually, multiple disk failures can be tolerated and data remains "
"available as long as the disks that fail are in different mirrors."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_raid10.xml:112
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"You can optionally configure a spare for each underlying mirrored array, or "
"configure a spare to serve a spare group that serves all mirrors."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_raid10.xml:121
#, no-c-format
msgid "10 (0+1)"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_raid10.xml:126
#, no-c-format
msgid "RAID 1 (mirror) built with RAID 0 (stripe) arrays"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_raid10.xml:131
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"RAID 0+1 provides high levels of I/O performance and data redundancy, but "
"slightly less fault tolerance than a 1+0. If multiple disks fail on one side "
"of the mirror, then the other mirror is available. However, if disks are "
"lost concurrently on both sides of the mirror, all data is lost."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_raid10.xml:138
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"This solution offers less disk fault tolerance than a 1+0 solution, but if "
"you need to perform maintenance or maintain the mirror on a different site, "
"you can take an entire side of the mirror offline and still have a fully "
"functional storage device. Also, if you lose the connection between the two "
"sites, either site operates independently of the other. That is not true if "
"you stripe the mirrored segments, because the mirrors are managed at a lower "
"level."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_raid10.xml:147
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"If a device fails, the mirror on that side fails because RAID 1 is not fault-"
"tolerant. Create a new RAID 0 to replace the failed side, then resynchronize "
"the mirrors."
msgstr ""

